# DRY · KISS · YAGNI — Core Coding Principles

These three principles apply to **every file, every language, every pull request**. They are not suggestions — treat violations as code smells that block merge.

---

## DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself

> *"Every piece of knowledge must have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system."*

### Rules
- If you write the same logic **twice**, extract it. If you write it a **third** time, it's a bug.
- Extract repeated code into:
  - **functions / methods** for behaviour
  - **constants / enums** for values
  - **types / interfaces** for data shapes
  - **components / templates** for UI patterns
- Shared utilities live in a dedicated `utils/` or `lib/` directory, not scattered in-place
- Configuration (URLs, thresholds, magic numbers) lives in **one place** and is referenced everywhere else
- Documentation duplication is as harmful as code duplication — a comment that restates what the code does is noise; a comment that explains *why* adds value

### Signals You Are Violating DRY
- Copy-pasting a code block and changing one variable
- The same validation logic in multiple files
- A magic number (`42`, `"admin"`, `3600`) appearing in more than one place
- Parallel structures that must always change together

### Caveat — Accidental DRY
Not all similarity is duplication. Two functions that look alike but represent **different domain concepts** should stay separate — premature unification creates wrong abstractions. Ask: *"Would these always change for the same reason?"* If no, keep them apart.

---

## KISS — Keep It Simple, Stupid

> *"Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication. The best code is the code that doesn't need to be explained."*

### Rules
- Choose the **simplest solution that correctly solves the problem**
- Prefer **readable over clever** — the next developer is you in six months
- One function does one thing; one class has one responsibility
- Avoid:
  - Deep nesting (≥ 3 levels is a warning sign — use guard clauses or extraction)
  - Long functions (rule of thumb: fits on one screen without scrolling)
  - Complex boolean expressions — extract them into a named predicate:
    ```ts
    // ❌ Hard to parse
    if (user.role === 'admin' && !user.suspended && (user.verified || user.legacyAccount)) { ... }

    // ✅ Self-documenting
    const canAccess = user.role === 'admin' && !user.suspended && isVerifiedUser(user);
    if (canAccess) { ... }
    ```
  - Unnecessary abstraction layers that add indirection without adding clarity
  - Over-engineering for hypothetical future requirements

### Signals You Are Violating KISS
- A new team member cannot understand a function in under 2 minutes
- You need a diagram to explain a single function's control flow
- A problem that has a 5-line solution has a 50-line implementation
- Code requires extensive inline comments to be understood (rewrite it instead)

### Simplicity Checklist (before committing)
- [ ] Could a junior developer follow this logic without asking questions?
- [ ] Is every abstraction layer earning its keep?
- [ ] Is the function/method name self-explanatory without reading the body?
- [ ] Are there any nested ternaries, chained methods, or magic expressions that could be named?

---

## YAGNI — You Aren't Gonna Need It

> *"Always implement things when you actually need them, never when you just foresee that you might need them."*

### Rules
- **Do not build features or abstractions that are not required right now**
- No "just in case" parameters, config flags, or extension points
- No generic frameworks built around a single use case
- No commented-out code "we might need later" — use version control for history
- No `TODO: add support for X someday` code paths that don't do anything yet
- Infrastructure (caching, queuing, microservices) should be introduced when the measured need arises, not speculatively

### What to Build vs. What to Skip

| ✅ Build it | ❌ Skip it |
|------------|-----------|
| Functionality in the current sprint | Functionality "we'll probably need" |
| Abstractions with ≥ 2 real use cases | Abstractions for 1 hypothetical use case |
| Config values that change between environments | Config flags for features not yet built |
| Error handling for known failure modes | Error handling for impossible scenarios |

### Signals You Are Violating YAGNI
- A function has a parameter that is never passed anything other than its default
- A class hierarchy exists for one concrete implementation
- A feature flag that has been `false` for more than one release cycle
- "Flexible" data structures designed for requirements that were never confirmed
- Tests for code paths that cannot be reached by current production logic

---

## How the Three Principles Work Together

| Scenario | Principle | Action |
|----------|-----------|--------|
| Same logic copy-pasted | DRY | Extract into a shared function |
| Clever one-liner nobody can read | KISS | Rewrite verbosely with a clear name |
| Generic plugin system for one use case | YAGNI | Delete the system, inline the logic |
| Abstraction with one implementation | YAGNI + KISS | Collapse into direct code |
| Magic number in three places | DRY | Extract to a named constant |
| 8-level deep class hierarchy | KISS + OOP | Flatten, use composition |

---

## Quick Self-Review Checklist

Before every commit, ask yourself:

- [ ] **DRY**: Is any logic, value, or structure defined more than once?
- [ ] **KISS**: Would a colleague understand this without explanation?
- [ ] **YAGNI**: Does every line of code serve a current, confirmed requirement?

If any answer is "no", fix it before pushing.
